##People can be trapped, but not stopped. | Guo Jing's diary of the siege of Wuhan | 2 / 2-2 / 4

Micro signal

Features an introduction to the refreshing flavor of the feminist hardcore

Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge in the sun on February 3
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

This is my friend Guo Jing's diary.

It records the real life experience and psychological feeling of the women who lived alone in Wuhan during the period of Fengcheng.

These words bear witness to Guo's journey from adapting to a sudden crisis to rebuilding her daily life to trying to help others.

Many readers have left comments in the hope that they will be able to follow up on their previous entries. Guo Jing and I discussed after the decision to move once every three days.

Those who want to keep up to date can follow@guo Jing, a social worker, on Weibo. At the end of the article has Guo Jing's personal wechat qr code, can also apply to add. She posts daily on her friends'network. (but please don't talk to Guo Jing privately to avoid adding to her burden.)

Some truths are easier said than done,
Problems in life don't just disappear in the blink of an eye.
2 February

A lot of friends say the news that sees pneumonia recently is so angry that can not sleep. There are plenty of things to be angry about, from children with cerebral palsy being quarantined and communities starving to death, to people being quarantined and cats being buried alive by community workers. In addition to anger, we have many complex emotions, including shock, sadness, and powerlessness.

Long-term exposure to such emotions without regulating the channel will affect the individual's physical and mental health. The sense of panic and powerlessness in the face of an epidemic can not go away, but it can abate. Some truths are easy to say, but the problems in life can not disappear in the moment of knowing them.

For two days I thought I had coughed a little too much and occasionally had a headache, which worried me. But I thought it was just nerves, so I went on with my daily life.

People can be trapped, but they can't stop. We need to find something to do. Wherever you are, if you have the ability to do something about it, and if you haven't found your place yet, I hope you have a good life.

Dinner on February 1st
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Last night's dinner was stir-fried dried bean curd with celery and rice porridge.

Evening as usual and friends chat, the topic of conversation is junior high school life. Some read youth and pain novels, some read classics. Everyone's junior high school has some loneliness, inferiority, depression, and efforts to explore and others, and the world relations. Some people are rebellious, like to challenge authority, and against the teacher. Someone suggested talking about the future, and we said it's too hard to talk about the future right now, and it could be over in five minutes.

Then there are those who share the inequalities they see at home, where women spend so much time cooking that it's hard to stop them. This is because they lack the means and means of public participation, and unpaid work such as cooking becomes the only way for them to achieve family status. We tried to cut the conversation short, worried it would be too short and One Thousand and One Nights. At the same time, we are very reluctant to give up, some people want to leave first and worry about missing important share.

Saw someone jump off a bridge in front of the cab this morning. I live just around the corner from where my friend said he would go years ago.

I started trying to get information out of pneumonia, and my friend Xiao Meili updated her podcast a few days ago, a bit idyllic, and listened to it over breakfast. This blog is kind of in tune with where I am right now. One feminist opened an owl mailbox on Douban, accepting submissions from women, listening to and responding to some of their confusion. The Owl box promoter is also looking for a place to do something meaningful.

Podcast link

Today's weather overcast up, went downstairs to find under a light rain, too lazy to go back to get an umbrella, still went out. A few days ago in the outside time is not long, in the outside did not take off the mask, even in the riverside. Thought I'd stay out a little longer today, bring some food and water. Then it started to rain harder and harder, and I stayed out for about two hours before I went home.

Interviewed four sanitation workers today. One of them is brother Pan, 58, from Wuhan. Pan, who has worked as a sanitation worker for four to five years, now works as a driver at Transfer station, delivering garbage and earns $5,000 a month. He signed a contract with Jiyuqiao Street. He's only been a driver for a year. His hours vary, depending on the amount of garbage, usually eight hours.

His wife, a community worker, did some advocacy work during the outbreak, helping people in the community to buy food. After the outbreak of pneumonia, he now goes home every day to take a bath, clothes washed once or twice a day. His wife does the washing and the cooking.

He was wearing a self-purchased N95 mask, which was issued as a disposable surgical mask. Elder brother Pan is not worried about the epidemic, said he did a good job of preventive measures. Everybody goes out to buy food only now, bought food to go home, also don't talk, won't infect. He said it would be better to go out now. It's too stuffy at home.

Transfer Station, February 2(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

On the way I saw a large yard selling vegetables at the gate. I bought some tomatoes, Parsley, corn and lettuce. The tomatoes and Parsley were ten dollars a kilo, the lettuce was eight dollars a kilo, and the corn was seven dollars a kilo.

Passing a party people's service center, several people wearing protective clothing, it seems to be in the distribution of food.

A man was fishing in a lake in the park.

Two volunteers are sitting at the gate of a large compound, looking at their mobile phones with slogans on the speakers.

Waist noodles shop or not open, the boss squatting in the door, he said the government issued a notice not to open the door, there is no place to go, idle.

February 2nd in the courtyard of the party member Mass Service Center
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Waist flower noodle shop on February 2(photo provided by Guo Jing)

In the afternoon, they received a call for help from their grandparents in Wuhan, who were in their 80s. They had CT scans showing lung problems, and they were waiting for confirmation that they needed nucleic acid tests. The caller's aunt is caring for two elderly people who need disposable gloves and hand sanitizer. I still have some at home, and his grandparents live not too far from me, so I thought I'd give them a ride. He said, "Don't do it. Special occasion. Let me be protective. ".

I contacted SF express, the courier said Wuhan City can be mailed, not to the field mail, the field to Wuhan can only send medical supplies, because now only air, liquid can not be sent. The courier said he couldn't mail it today, and he couldn't pick it up from the delivery cabinet, so he had to go to the delivery place. I was GONNA go tomorrow, but the guy said the family's got supplies now.

Vegetable stalls on February 2(photo provided by Guo Jing)

3 February

Going out every day became an important part of my routine. In fact, I do not feel the need to go out, but I still insist on paranoia.

What am I holding on to? The city will not be suddenly unsealed tomorrow, and the outside world will not change dramatically in a day.

It's a subtle revolt, looking for real information in a block of information, looking for connections in isolation, looking for some certainty in uncertainty.

Last night's dinner was sauteed pork with garlic and porridge.

Dinner on February 2nd
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Talking to my friends at night. Some danced with their mother yesterday. Others listened to Virginia Woolf's book while playing with Legos. She said women should focus on their relationship with reality.

Last night in the chat, I occasionally do some online contact of the voluntary work, but do not want to miss the chat, open video, listening to their voices, very reassuring.

In the morning by outside Chirp bird call wake up, get up to look out of the window is gray, more than ten began to clear up. After exercising and having breakfast, I opened the door to go out and found myself without a mask. It's hard to let your guard down. Someone's jumping rope downstairs.

On February 2nd, a man was fishing by the lake
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

These two days on the road to see most of the sanitation workers began to wear disposable masks.

Interviewed two sanitation workers and a property company cleaner today. Big Sister Liu is 50 years old today. Her husband is from Wuhan. She came to Wuhan after getting married. Sister Liu works in a small community and walks to work for 20-30 minutes a day.

She was wearing a hazmat suit and a 3m mask. The suit and the mask were issued by the property company, but they weren't enough, so her suit was old.

The owners don't even go out anymore, so they just leave their trash at the door. Liu said cleaning staff are older people, many of whom are too old to work for fear of infection. I asked her why she was still doing it, and she said someone had to do it.

Because of wearing protective clothing, kept sweating, wet, every day to go home to take a bath. The House is protected, too, like cleaning with 84. She does all the work.

Janitors in Hazmat suits on February 3rd
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

The Sun came out, so I went to the river for a walk. Someone's taking a nap, someone's exercising.

The old man on the monkey bars is 64 years old and fit. In his 40s, he became a member of the top three and developed diabetes. Instead of taking his medicine, he began to exercise from then on. He also went out every day during the outbreak. Three generations live in the same house, and they don't leave the house. He wasn't afraid. He was in better health. He went out to buy vegetables.

In the afternoon, I recorded a podcast with Mei Li, sharing my life under lock and key. I'm glad I started keeping a journal, because it became part of my daily routine.
People take a nap by the river on Feb. 3(photo provided by Guo Jing)

4 February

A few days ago saw a person posted on the friend circle, wrote: "The news of Fengcheng Fengcun only a few days, how many men in a state of anxiety, imagine how many girls are such a day all year round. "

The blockade is partly a way for men to experience women's lack of public life. Many married women are forced to focus on their families after marriage, even if they have a full time job. After work, they do the washing and cooking, take care of the children, and do a lot of underappreciated housework. Their public life is shrinking, they have less time to talk to colleagues and friends, and they are more devoted to their families than to themselves.

Last night's dinner was celery with chicken breast and Porridge.

February 2 volunteers (photo provided by Guo Jing)

Talking to my friends at night. The day before the earthquake in Chengdu, we talked about the Wenchuan County earthquake of 2008. Everyone told stories of how they were, many of them in high school, some of them leaving the classroom with their history books, some of them continuing their classes in the city where the quake was not strong, some of them feeling like they were going to die, and she fantasized that when she died, she would be studied as a relic like Pambet.

We remember some touching stories at that time, such as the children to drink coke after being rescued, some people remember not to evacuate students and first left the classroom fan ran. At that time, Fan ran was almost universally reviled. Now I don't think running is that bad.

We've reexamined collectivism and heroism. In the face of disaster, we create dedicated heroes, belittle the so-called "selfish" behavior, but in fact many seemingly selfish behavior is only people's self-preservation. The collectivism has a strong emotional appeal, and can even create resentment and even hatred, such as the Chinese hate the Japanese. It makes us lose sight of who we are.

It's a good thing that we recognize the vulnerability of our health care workers today, as well as their dedication.

Street view of Hubu Alley on Feb. 4(image provided by Guo Jing)

Interviewed three sanitation workers today. Chen, 45, has been working as a sanitation worker for a year. She is Xiaogan people, her husband is also a sanitation worker, a family of three people in Wuhan Rent. She has a sanitation contract, social security. Since the closure of the city, the unit issued a total of 16 masks, she said not enough, also issued a labor protection gloves, she is not used to use, on their own wool gloves.

Big Sister Chen now daily bath, change clothes, the home also every day disinfection. She does most of this. I asked Chen if she needed anything. She said she didn't need anything. Now there are trash cans for masks on the street, and Chen said there will be people wearing protective clothing to clean them up. When I was talking to sister Chen, some men in uniform came up to me. I quickly gave sister Chen a bag of masks, and rode away.

After riding about 100 meters, I saw an armed police hospital. I couldn't see anything out of the ordinary.

On February 4th, there were lots of vegetable buns at the gate of the community
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Passing by a community today, the door put a lot of cabbage, security in the temperature, there are residents out to take the temperature after the temperature into the community.

We passed a fenced-in studio and a hotel today, with several men in Hazmat suits outside. I saw some cars on the side of the road posted "control of the epidemic, convenient for the masses, serve the community" , the driver in the rest.

On the way, I saw the Wuhan Red Cross Training Center, which was closed, and SF express, which was still open. There's an open shop called Mount Wutai's good luck name.

I also passed by Hube Lane. It's been about 12 years since I was here, and there are only a few people here now. There was a country restaurant with the door open, and a man in uniform came to pick up takeout.

February 4, Wuhan Red Cross Training Center
SF Express, which is still in business
(photo courtesy of Guo Jing)

I was walking home from the river, and someone was running with the dog, and the dog was wearing a mask.

Someone suspected in the river side sex, the woman sitting on the stone bench, the man lying on her, the man's pants unbuttoned half.

Two old men were sunning themselves on the Bank of the river.

I took my mask off in a no-man's-land and breathed it in smoothly for a while, feeling bound again the moment I put it on.

A man runs with his dog on Feb. 4(photo provided by Guo Jing)

People Bask in the sun on the riverbank on Feb. 4(photo provided by Guo Jing)

I want to be a connection,
I want to be able to connect with more people and act together.

Because of wearing protective clothing, kept sweating, wet, every day to go home to take a bath. The House is protected, too, like cleaning with 84. She does all the work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Janitors in Hazmat suits on February 3rd
(image courtesy of Guo Jing)

Janitors in Hazmat suits on February 3rd

The Sun came out, so I went to the river for a walk. Someone's taking a nap, someone's exercising.

The old man on the monkey bars is 64 years old and fit. In his 40s, he became a member of the top three and developed diabetes. Instead of taking his medicine, he began to exercise from then on. He also went out every day during the outbreak. Three generations live in the same house, and they don't leave the house. He wasn't afraid. He was in better health. He went out to buy vegetables.

In the afternoon, I recorded a podcast with Mei Li, sharing my life under lock and key. I'm glad I started keeping a journal, because it became part of my daily routine.

4 February

A few days ago saw a person posted on the friend circle, wrote: "The news of Fengcheng Fengcun only a few days, how many men in a state of anxiety, imagine how many girls are such a day all year round. "

The blockade is partly a way for men to experience women's lack of public life. Many married women are forced to focus on their families after marriage, even if they have a full time job. After work, they do the washing and cooking, take care of the children, and do a lot of underappreciated housework. Their public life is shrinking, they have less time to talk to colleagues and friends, and they are more devoted to their families than to themselves.

Last night's dinner was celery with chicken breast and Porridge.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 2 volunteers (photo provided by Guo Jing)

Talking to my friends at night. The day before the earthquake in Chengdu, we talked about the Wenchuan County earthquake of 2008. Everyone told stories of how they were, many of them in high school, some of them leaving the classroom with their history books, some of them continuing their classes in the city where the quake was not strong, some of them feeling like they were going to die, and she fantasized that when she died, she would be studied as a relic like Pambet.

We remember some touching stories at that time, such as the children to drink coke after being rescued, some people remember not to evacuate students and first left the classroom fan ran. At that time, Fan ran was almost universally reviled. Now I don't think running is that bad.

We've reexamined collectivism and heroism. In the face of disaster, we create dedicated heroes, belittle the so-called "selfish" behavior, but in fact many seemingly selfish behavior is only people's self-preservation. The collectivism has a strong emotional appeal, and can even create resentment and even hatred, such as the Chinese hate the Japanese. It makes us lose sight of who we are.

It's a good thing that we recognize the vulnerability of our health care workers today, as well as their dedication.

Interviewed three sanitation workers today. Chen, 45, has been working as a sanitation worker for a year. She is Xiaogan people, her husband is also a sanitation worker, a family of three people in Wuhan Rent. She has a sanitation contract, social security. Since the closure of the city, the unit issued a total of 16 masks, she said not enough, also issued a labor protection gloves, she is not used to use, on their own wool gloves.

Big Sister Chen now daily bath, change clothes, the home also every day disinfection. She does most of this. I asked Chen if she needed anything. She said she didn't need anything. Now there are trash cans for masks on the street, and Chen said there will be people wearing protective clothing to clean them up. When I was talking to sister Chen, some men in uniform came up to me. I quickly gave sister Chen a bag of masks, and rode away.

After riding about 100 meters, I saw an armed police hospital. I couldn't see anything out of the ordinary.

Someone suspected in the river side sex, the woman sitting on the stone bench, the man lying on her, the man's pants unbuttoned half.

Two old men were sunning themselves on the Bank of the river.

I took my mask off in a no-man's-land and breathed it in smoothly for a while, feeling bound again the moment I put it on.
